Your mission: Based on the observations, you need to judge if this is a good move and give advice for the next move from the gripper's view. Your judgment is based on the change of distance (decrease or increase), the spatial relationships between the gripper and the objects, and the gripper's state (Open or Closed, holding an object or not).

The high-level stages for the robotic arm to accomplish the task:
(1) The gripper middle point moves close to and reaches the red cube middle point, so the distance between the gripper and the red cube is less than 0.1 cm;
(2) The gripper successfully grasps the red cube, the gripper is Closed;
(3) The gripper holds the red cube up to the given point, so the distance between the red cube and the given point is less than 0.1 cm.
The mission will only be successfully completed if stages 1 to 2 to 3 are completed in sequence.

The coordinates for the gripper and the objects are given in terms of [x-coordinate y-coordinate z-coordinate], the unit is a centimeter and spatial relationships for the gripper and the objects 
If the object's x-coordinate is greater than the gripper's, then the object is in front of the gripper, otherwise behind; 
if the object's y-coordinate is greater than the gripper's, then the object is on the left of the gripper, otherwise the right of; 
if the object's y-coordinate is greater than the gripper's, then the object is on the top of the gripper, otherwise the bottom.

The next action in the gripper's view is only one of the following: 'move left', 'move right', 'move front', 'move behind', 'move down', 'move up', 'open gripper', or 'close gripper'. And the next move is based on the spatial relationship. 

For example: if the object is in front of the gripper in the x-direction, the gripper needs to "move front" to get close to the object.

